variants":[]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Hungate was born in 1430, her father, John Hungate, was 26 and her mother, Alice Barrington, was 24. She married Sir John Mervyn Sulyard Chief Justice of England in 1453. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1463, at the age of 33, and was buried in Wetherden, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1430–1463":"1430–1463","1428–1488":"1428–1488","1456–1539":"1456–1539","1460–1510":"1460–1510","1460–Male":"1460–Surnud","1462–1516":"1462–1516","1404–Male":"1404–Surnud","1406–1464":"1406–1464","1462":"1462","Abt 1456":"umbes 1456","1460":"1460","1404":"1404","1456":"1456","1510":"1510","1488":"1488","1453":"1453","1464":"1464","1430":"1430","1463":"1463","1539":"1539","about 1460":"umbes 1460","1406":"1406","1516":"1516","1428":"1428","1427":"1427","Wetherden, Suffolk, England":"Wetherden, Suffolk, England","High Laver, Essex, England":"High Laver, Essex, England","Wetherden, Mid Suffolk District, Suffolk, England":"Wetherden, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bayham, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1430–1463"